WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:10.320
Alright, so here's the general setup&nbsp;
that explains what we're doing here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:16.480
We're going to look not at this particular&nbsp;
equation but at a more general equation which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:24.160
is just like it: x squared plus bx equals&nbsp;
c. So there's more letters now. There's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:30.880
letter x which represents our mystery unknown&nbsp;
number, and now there's letters b and c which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:36.560
are not representing mystery numbers anymore;&nbsp;
they're representing constant given numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:46.640
It's just that we're not specific about which ones&nbsp;
they are. So here and here, b was 10 and c was 39,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:52.480
but we want to explain the algorithm in a way that&nbsp;
doesn't depend on which particular numbers we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.480 --> 00:01:00.000
using, so we use b and c. Okay, but these b and&nbsp;
c letters are playing a different role from x.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.400
We imagine that b and c are known&nbsp;
to us and we have to solve for x.

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:15.120
So what do we do? Well, we mimic what we did up&nbsp;
here. We add b over 2 squared to both sides—that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:24.640
the little square that we're adding there—and now&nbsp;
what's on the left-hand side is a perfect square.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:31.120
Just like this here is a perfect square.&nbsp;
It is equal to x plus b over 2 all squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:37.520
and let's check that. If we square this,&nbsp;
we get x squared plus 2 times the product&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:44.160
2 times x times b over 2—that's exactly bx—and&nbsp;
b over 2 squared, well, there it is right there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:50.320
And this thing here, we can just&nbsp;
write it as c plus b squared over 4.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:02:00.480
Now in this form, it's much like this equation&nbsp;
here. We take x plus b over 2 squared equals this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:09.440
so x plus b over 2 will be the square root of this&nbsp;
where we're introducing a new terminology—the idea&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:16.000
of a square root, a number whose square is this.&nbsp;
So we end up getting x equals the square root of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.840
c plus b squared over 4 minus b over 2 because&nbsp;
the b over 2 comes around to the other side.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.200 --> 00:02:30.320
We're introducing this third notation for the&nbsp;
square root; that was an innovation also due&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:38.240
to the Arabs. So for example, the square root of&nbsp;
16 is 4, the square root of 25 is 5, and so on.

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:44.160
Alright, let's have a look at this example&nbsp;
which mimics exactly what we're doing here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:51.520
but rewritten in a more modern form that's&nbsp;
familiar to all students of algebra. So here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:58.640
is the modern way of rewriting what Al-Khwarizmi&nbsp;
did in that previous example. Usually, today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.640 --> 00:03:06.480
we think about a quadratic equation in this form:&nbsp;
ax squared plus bx plus c equals zero, where a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:13.200
b, and c are three specific given numbers, and x&nbsp;
is an unknown number that we're trying to find.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:19.200
We'll assume that this coefficient a is&nbsp;
non-zero so we really have a quadratic equation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:28.240
Now there's a step-by-step procedure to&nbsp;
transform this equation into an equation for x,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:35.200
and this is a well-known formula that all students&nbsp;
learn. How to get that solution is almost as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:40.640
important; perhaps maybe it's more important&nbsp;
than the solution itself. So it's something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:46.880
that all serious students of mathematics should&nbsp;
know—the various steps to go from here to here.

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:55.040
So what do we do? The first thing is we take the&nbsp;
a and we take it as a factor: a times x squared&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.040 --> 00:04:00.160
plus b over a times x, and we bring the c&nbsp;
to the other side, giving us minus c there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:09.760
We divide by a, so this a comes over to the other&nbsp;
side as minus c over a, and what's inside here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:14.320
Now we complete the square in exactly the&nbsp;
same way as we did on the previous slide.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:20.240
We do that by adding the square&nbsp;
of half of this coefficient&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:27.840
b over 2a, so we add the square of that to both&nbsp;
sides, so that it is still a valid equation.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:36.080
That makes what's on the left-hand side here a&nbsp;
perfect square: (x plus b over 2a) all squared.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:43.920
When we simplify what's on the right,&nbsp;
the common denominator is 4a squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:52.480
and there will be a b squared from here. When we&nbsp;
take this over a common denominator of 4a squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.480 --> 00:05:00.480
we have to multiply the top by 4a, giving us&nbsp;
b squared minus 4ac in the numerator here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:09.440
So this squared equals this quantity, so what's&nbsp;
inside is the square root of the right-hand side.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:14.800
We put the square root of the numerator and the&nbsp;
square root of the denominator, which will be 2a.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:22.640
Because the square root has an ambiguity&nbsp;
in terms of sign, if we have one solution,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:27.360
the negative of it is also a solution. We put&nbsp;
a plus or minus here, telling us that we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:34.480
either take plus this or minus this. The square&nbsp;
root is by convention always a positive number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:39.200
so when we talk about the square root&nbsp;
of 9, we always mean 3, not minus 3.

00:05:41.520 --> 00:05:46.560
To go from here to here, it's simply a question&nbsp;
of taking this b over 2a and bringing it to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:46.560 --> 00:05:52.320
other side. So finally, x equals minus b plus&nbsp;
or minus the square root of b squared minus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.320 --> 00:06:00.000
4ac all over 2a. This is a well-known formula&nbsp;
for all students, and in our context, we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:07.920
actually use this as long as this condition&nbsp;
is satisfied: that what's inside here, this b&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:14.320
squared minus 4ac term, had better be a square&nbsp;
because we want to take the square root of it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:20.720
So in particular, it's going to be positive; it's&nbsp;
got to be positive and it's got to be a square&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.680 --> 00:06:26.880
because right now we're still working in&nbsp;
the realm entirely of rational numbers.

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:34.960
Okay, so that's good. That's the classic&nbsp;
formula for the quadratic equation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.520 --> 00:06:42.160
Next time, we're going to talk about an&nbsp;
important ingredient to this business, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:47.440
is: how do you actually find a square root?&nbsp;
We've been assuming that you can kind of do it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:53.520
but how do you actually find the square root of a&nbsp;
number? That's a very interesting algorithm which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.520 --> 00:07:01.840
we'll discuss next time. I hope you'll join me for&nbsp;
that. I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

